# C Programming Projects

This folder contains focused C projects covering modular software design, data structures, embedded systems, signal processing, communication protocols, memory management, concurrency, real-time processing, software testing, and performance analysis.

The current projects focus on practical C implementations with structured architecture, reusable modules, defensive programming, clear memory ownership, build automation, testing, and debugging.

The planned projects extend the collection toward real-time firmware, fixed-point DSP, lock-free data structures, protocol development, deterministic memory management, hardware abstraction, fault handling, and production-oriented verification.

## Objectives

The main objectives of this folder are to:

* design modular and maintainable C applications;
* implement reusable software components;
* develop embedded and firmware-oriented programming skills;
* apply C to DSP, wireless, sensor, and communication applications;
* manage memory safely and efficiently;
* define clear interfaces between software modules;
* implement robust error handling;
* verify software using unit tests and integration tests;
* detect memory and undefined-behaviour problems;
* measure processing time, memory usage, latency, and throughput;
* build portable applications using GCC, Clang, Make, and CMake;
* demonstrate practical C programming for technical engineering roles.

## Technical Areas

The projects cover the following areas:

* modular C architecture;
* source and header file organization;
* opaque data structures;
* pointers and memory ownership;
* static and dynamic memory management;
* callbacks and function pointers;
* generic data structures;
* circular buffers and queues;
* event-driven state machines;
* sensor-data acquisition;
* digital signal processing;
* fixed-point arithmetic;
* communication protocol parsing;
* UART, SPI, and I²C software interfaces;
* real-time data pipelines;
* multithreading and synchronization;
* C11 atomic operations;
* deterministic memory allocation;
* hardware abstraction;
* error handling and fault recovery;
* static and dynamic analysis;
* unit, integration, stress, and regression testing;
* performance benchmarking;
* continuous integration.

