# Software Architecture

Each larger project should use a clear layered architecture.

```text
Application
    |
    v
Service Layer
    |
    v
Algorithm or Protocol Layer
    |
    v
Platform Abstraction
    |
    v
Operating System or Hardware
```

A typical project may use the following organization:

```text
project-name/
│
├── include/
│   ├── project_api.h
│   └── project_types.h
│
├── src/
│   ├── project_api.c
│   ├── internal_module.c
│   └── internal_module.h
│
├── tests/
│   ├── test_main.c
│   ├── test_project_api.c
│   └── test_internal_module.c
│
├── examples/
│   └── example_application.c
│
├── benchmarks/
│   └── benchmark_main.c
│
├── docs/
│   └── architecture.md
│
├── CMakeLists.txt
└── README.md
```

## Public Interfaces

Public header files should expose only the information required by other modules.

Internal data should remain inside source files or private header files.

```c
typedef struct CircularBuffer CircularBuffer;

CircularBuffer *circular_buffer_create(
    size_t capacity,
    size_t element_size
);

int circular_buffer_write(
    CircularBuffer *buffer,
    const void *element
);

int circular_buffer_read(
    CircularBuffer *buffer,
    void *element
);

void circular_buffer_destroy(
    CircularBuffer *buffer
);
```

This design allows the implementation to change without modifying the public interface.

## Error Handling

Functions that may fail should return explicit status values.

```c
typedef enum
{
    STATUS_OK = 0,
    STATUS_INVALID_ARGUMENT,
    STATUS_OUT_OF_MEMORY,
    STATUS_BUFFER_FULL,
    STATUS_BUFFER_EMPTY,
    STATUS_TIMEOUT,
    STATUS_DATA_CORRUPTION,
    STATUS_NOT_INITIALIZED,
    STATUS_INTERNAL_ERROR
} StatusCode;
```

Example function:

```c
StatusCode process_samples(
    const int16_t *samples,
    size_t sample_count,
    ProcessingResult *result
);
```

The caller should verify the returned value before using the output.

## Memory Ownership

Each interface should clearly define:

* which module allocates the memory;
* which module owns the memory;
* which module may modify the data;
* which function releases the memory;
* whether a pointer may be retained;
* whether null pointers are accepted;
* how buffer sizes are specified;
* whether data is copied or referenced.

Clear ownership rules reduce:

* memory leaks;
* double-free errors;
* use-after-free errors;
* invalid pointer access;
* unexpected data modification.

# Coding Guidelines

The projects follow these general practices:

* use meaningful names;
* keep functions focused;
* separate module responsibilities;
* avoid hidden side effects;
* validate public-function arguments;
* use `const` where data should not be modified;
* use fixed-width integer types when binary size matters;
* check numeric conversions;
* avoid unnecessary global variables;
* avoid unnecessary dynamic allocation;
* check all return values;
* release resources on every failure path;
* isolate platform-specific code;
* document assumptions and limitations;
* compile without warnings.

## Fixed-Width Integer Types

Projects involving embedded systems, DSP, or protocol data should use `<stdint.h>`.

```c
#include <stdint.h>

uint8_t message_type;
int16_t sensor_sample;
uint32_t timestamp_ticks;
int64_t accumulated_energy;
```

## Buffer Length Handling

Functions that write to a buffer should receive the available capacity explicitly.

```c
StatusCode encode_message(
    const Message *message,
    uint8_t *output_buffer,
    size_t output_capacity,
    size_t *encoded_length
);
```

The function must validate the capacity before writing data.

# Build Instructions

Projects may use GCC, Clang, Make, or CMake.

## GCC Build

```bash
gcc \
    -std=c11 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -Wconversion \
    -Wshadow \
    -Wformat=2 \
    -Wundef \
    -Wstrict-prototypes \
    -Wmissing-prototypes \
    src/main.c \
    src/module.c \
    -Iinclude \
    -o application
```

## Debug Build

```bash
gcc \
    -std=c11 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -g3 \
    -O0 \
    src/main.c \
    src/module.c \
    -Iinclude \
    -o application
```

## Optimized Build

```bash
gcc \
    -std=c11 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -O2 \
    -DNDEBUG \
    src/main.c \
    src/module.c \
    -Iinclude \
    -o application
```

## Sanitizer Build

```bash
gcc \
    -std=c11 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -fsanitize=address,undefined \
    -fno-omit-frame-pointer \
    -g \
    src/main.c \
    src/module.c \
    -Iinclude \
    -o application_sanitized
```

Run the program:

```bash
./application_sanitized
```

## CMake Build

```bash
cmake -S . -B build
cmake --build build
```

Run tests:

```bash
ctest --test-dir build --output-on-failure
```

# Testing Strategy

Each project should include more than a single demonstration run.

Testing may include:

* unit testing;
* integration testing;
* boundary-value testing;
* invalid-input testing;
* error-path testing;
* memory-leak detection;
* concurrency stress testing;
* performance benchmarking;
* regression testing;
* fuzz testing.

## Normal-Operation Tests

Examples include:

* valid configuration;
* expected sample range;
* normal buffer operation;
* valid protocol frames;
* correct state transitions;
* expected filter output.

## Boundary Tests

Examples include:

* zero-length input;
* one-element input;
* maximum supported length;
* full buffer;
* empty buffer;
* maximum counter value;
* timer wraparound;
* minimum and maximum numeric values.

## Invalid-Input Tests

Examples include:

* null pointers;
* invalid enumeration values;
* malformed files;
* corrupted protocol frames;
* invalid buffer sizes;
* unsupported configuration values;
* invalid state-machine events.

## Resource-Failure Tests

Examples include:

* memory-allocation failure;
* unavailable files;
* communication timeout;
* queue overflow;
* simulated hardware failure;
* worker-thread creation failure.

## Concurrency Tests

Examples include:

* repeated producer-consumer operation;
* shutdown during active processing;
* queue saturation;
* simultaneous reads and writes;
* long-duration stress testing.

# Static Analysis

Static-analysis tools may be used to identify problems before runtime.

Example:

```bash
cppcheck \
    --enable=all \
    --std=c11 \
    --suppress=missingIncludeSystem \
    include src tests
```

Static analysis can help detect:

* uninitialized variables;
* invalid pointer usage;
* suspicious conditions;
* unreachable code;
* unsafe type conversions;
* unchecked return values;
* resource leaks;
* incorrect conditions.

# Dynamic Analysis

Valgrind may be used on supported systems.

```bash
valgrind \
    --leak-check=full \
    --show-leak-kinds=all \
    --track-origins=yes \
    ./application
```

Dynamic analysis can identify:

* memory leaks;
* invalid reads;
* invalid writes;
* uninitialized memory;
* use-after-free errors;
* incorrect memory release.

# Performance Evaluation

Projects involving real-time processing, communication, queues, memory allocation, or DSP should include measurable results.

Possible measurements include:

* average execution time;
* maximum observed execution time;
* processing throughput;
* queue latency;
* allocation latency;
* memory usage;
* stack usage;
* heap usage;
* dropped-message count;
* dropped-sample count;
* CPU utilization.

### Example Output

```text
Samples processed:          1,000,000
Average processing time:    2.4 us/sample
Maximum processing time:    4.9 us/sample
Memory usage:               18.2 KB
Dropped samples:            0
Processing failures:        0
```

Performance reports should identify:

* processor or test platform;
* operating system;
* compiler;
* compiler version;
* optimization setting;
* input size;
* number of iterations;
* measurement method.

# Continuous Integration

GitHub Actions may be used to automate:

* GCC builds;
* Clang builds;
* debug builds;
* optimized builds;
* sanitizer tests;
* unit tests;
* static analysis;
* formatting checks;
* code-coverage generation.

A possible workflow may include:

```text
GCC Debug Build
GCC Optimized Build
Clang Debug Build
Sanitizer Build
Static Analysis
Unit Tests
```

# Documentation Requirements

Each project README should include:

* project overview;
* engineering objective;
* architecture;
* module descriptions;
* algorithm description;
* interface description;
* build instructions;
* execution instructions;
* test procedure;
* example output;
* performance results;
* limitations;
* planned improvements.

Larger projects should also contain:

* architecture diagrams;
* data-flow diagrams;
* state diagrams;
* API documentation;
* verification results;
* benchmark results.

# Skills Demonstrated

This project collection demonstrates experience with:

* C11 programming;
* modular software architecture;
* embedded C;
* systems programming;
* firmware-oriented development;
* reusable data structures;
* pointer handling;
* memory ownership;
